    {
      "id": "de1bf4dbc650026d146930ba073d0955780ad343",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2011-12-16 17:55:20.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\nChanges look pretty good. However, I don't think that we can make the test xattr size a full 65536 bytes when the \"mid-sized\" xattr support lands. It needs a small amount of overhead to fit the xattr_header. It would be something like 65536-64=65472 bytes. \n\nInstead of hard coding the maximum xattr size into all of the tests it should be a constant set by large_xattr_enabled(). Maybe instead of returning a Boolean true/false value it should be renamed large_xattr_size() and return the maximum xattr size?\n\nThe other issue is that these tests _could_ test the large xattr support, but do not.  If they are left disabled then it is unlikely that they will ever be enabled. At a minimum, once the ldiskfs patch lands some conf-sanity test should format a small large_ filesystem and always test this feature.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
